                                                                                  Network Penetration Testing 

Steps :

1. Finding All Active Hosts
Use tools like Nmap, Angry IP Scanner, or Netdiscover to identify live devices in the network.

2. Discovering Open Ports
Perform port scanning using tools like Nmap or Masscan to identify open ports on active hosts.

3. Detecting Service Versions
Run version scanning (nmap -sV) to detect which services are running on the open ports and what versions they are.

4. Researching Exploits
Search for known vulnerabilities and exploits for those specific versions on websites like:

Google
Exploit-DB = https://www.exploit-db.com/
https://vulners.com/search/cvss
https://www.rapid7.com/db/
                                     
Searchsploit :
1. searchsploit keyword
•	This command is used to search the local Exploit-DB database for exploits related to the keyword you provide.
•	Example: searchsploit apache
•	This will show a list of exploits related to "apache".
________________________________________
2. searchsploit -p edbid
•	This command shows detailed information about the exploit identified by the exploit database ID (edbid).
•	The -p option displays the path to the exploit code on your system and the URL to the Exploit-DB page for more info.
•	Example : searchsploit -p 12345
•	Output will include something like:

Exploit Path: /usr/share/exploitdb/exploits/linux/local/12345.c
Exploit-DB URL: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/12345
________________________________________
3. searchsploit -m edbid
•	This command copies the exploit file from the local predefined path to your current working directory.
•	The -m option stands for mirror (copy).
•	Example: searchsploit -m 12345


5. If Exploit Found – Exploitation

If a working exploit is found (manual or through Metasploit):
Follow the exploit steps from the source (e.g., Exploit-DB or GitHub).
Exploit the vulnerability to gain access (e.g., shell, reverse shell, etc.)


6. Post-Exploitation (Optional)
After access: try privilege escalation, gathering sensitive info, or checking lateral movement possibilities.

7. Reporting
Document everything:
IP address of the host
Port and service version
Vulnerability name and source
Exploitation method and impact
Screenshots, logs, and proof-of-concept

Provide risk rating and fix recommendation for each issue.
